 from scholars, activists, and artists from across disciplines, professions, and creative practices, this book explores the extent to which copyright has expanded into every facet of society and reveals how our capacities to actually deal fairly with cultural goods has suffered in the process. In order to drive conversations about the cultural worlds Canadians imagine, and the policy reforms we need to realize these visions, we need Dynamic Fair Dealing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCopyright and electronic data processingzCanada. 0aCopyrightzCanada. 0aElectronic information resourcesxFair use (Copyright)zCanada. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aWershler, Darren , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aZeilinger, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266561340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442665613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442665613.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK